The samples were examined at various scales, such as 200 nm, 100 nm, 20 nm and 2 μm using the FE-SEM (Fig. 2
                        ). “The investigation revealed various types of information depending on size and morphology.” The NiO morphology is depicted in Fig. 1(a). The uniform leaf-like structures (Fig. 2
                        (b–c)) and jasmine-like nanoflowers have extremely porous architectures with larger open spaces, enabling greater charge storage and increased specific capacitance [6]. The morphology shown in Fig. 2(d) closely resembles a jasmine leaf-like structure [7]. Regardless of the preparation method, the performance of the supercapacitor is improved by the contact between the material's surface and the electrolyte. The presence of scattered nanoparticles on the jasmine-like nanoflowers induces the formation of porous structures by metal oxides in carbon dots [8].
